							} else {
								chosen_locations_div.style.display = "none";
							}

                      <span class="acalog_catalog_name">
                       2022-2023 Undergraduate Catalog
                      </span>
                      <h1 id="acalog-page-title">
                       Computer Science Major, BS in Computer Science
                      </h1>
                     </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                     <td>
                      <hr/>
                     </td>
                    </tr>
                   </tbody>
                  </table>
                  <div class="program_description">
                   <p>
                    Students may choose from a wide spectrum of courses covering various aspects of computer science, computer engineering, and related fields. Students must meet the design, depth, and breadth requirements in the department in their selection of these courses. Students are encouraged to discuss an appropriate program with their advisors.
                   </p>
                   <h3>
                    Progression Policies and Requirements
                   </h3>
                   <p>
                    The department requires at least a C in every computer engineering, computer science, electrical engineering, and mathematics course used for the undergraduate degrees.
                   </p>
                   <p>
                    Progression of departmental undergraduate students to the upper-division programs of the department is competitive and is based on the space available in the department. Factors considered in the decision include overall grade point average, grades earned in courses required in the lower-division curricula of the department and Tickle College of Engineering, and seriousness of purpose and interest in departmental programs as exemplified by regular and orderly progress through the prescribed curriculum without abuse of withdrawal and course repeat privileges.
                   </p>
                   <h3>
                    <strong>
                     uTrack Requirements
                    </strong>
                   </h3>
                   <p>
                    Universal Tracking (uTrack) is an academic monitoring system designed to help students stay on track for timely graduation. In order to remain on track, students must complete the minimum requirements for each tracking semester, known as milestones. Milestones include successful completion of specified courses and/or attainment of a minimum GPA. uTrack requirements only affect full-time, degree-seeking students.
                   </p>
                  </div>
                 </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                 <td class="width" colspan="4">

                       <td style="text-align:center;vertical-align:top;width:2%;">

                       </td>

                      <tr>
                       <td style="text-align:center;vertical-align:top;width:2%;">
                        <sup>
                         1
                        </sup>
                       </td>
                       <td style="text-align:justify;">
                        Beginning students who have had high school computer science and/or who have had significant programming experience (e.g. summer institute study, special research projects, home laboratory) are invited to apply during the summer to the head of the department for permission to take a proficiency examination for
                        <a href="#tt9556" id="tt9556" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184123&amp;print', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" rel="remote /ajax/preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184123&amp;display_options[location]=tooltip&amp;show" target="_blank">
                         COSC 101 - Introduction to Programming
                        </a>
                        <span style="display: none !important">
                        </span>
                        , Introduction to Computer Science. If a satisfactory grade is made on the examination, credit will be allowed for
                        <a href="#tt9888" id="tt9888" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184123&amp;print', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" rel="remote /ajax/preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184123&amp;display_options[location]=tooltip&amp;show" target="_blank">
                         COSC 101
                        </a>
                        <span style="display: none !important">
                        </span>
                        . The Department of Electrical Engineering and Computer Science also gives credit in
                        <a href="#tt8392" id="tt8392" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184123&amp;print', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" rel="remote /ajax/preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184123&amp;display_options[location]=tooltip&amp;show" target="_blank">
                         COSC 101
                        </a>
                        <span style="display: none !important">
                        </span>
                        to students who receive a score of 3 or better on the Computer Science Advanced Placement A Examination.
                       </td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                       <td style="text-align:center;vertical-align:top;width:2%;">
                        <sup>
                         2
                        </sup>
                       </td>
                       <td style="text-align:justify;">
                        Chosen from
                        <a href="preview_program.php?catoid=34&amp;poid=17209" target="_blank">
                         Volunteer Core
                        </a>
                        <span style="display: none !important">
                        </span>
                        list. Students should try to select courses that satisfy approved areas and
                        <a href="preview_program.php?catoid=34&amp;poid=17218" target="_blank">
                         Engaged Inquiries
                        </a>
                        <span style="display: none !important">
                        </span>
                        category. Students must have a minimum of 9 credit hours in at least two subject areas for
                        <a href="preview_program.php?catoid=34&amp;poid=17218" target="_blank">
                         Engaged Inquiries
                        </a>
                        <span style="display: none !important">
                        </span>
                        .

                        <a href="#tt2060" id="tt2060" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180922&amp;print', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" rel="remote /ajax/preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180922&amp;display_options[location]=tooltip&amp;show" target="_blank">

                        <a href="#tt6657" id="tt6657" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180922&amp;print', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" rel="remote /ajax/preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180922&amp;display_options[location]=tooltip&amp;show" target="_blank">
                         ENGL 102

                         ENGL 355
                        </a>
                        <span style="display: none !important">
                        </span>
                        *.
                       </td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                       <td style="text-align:center;vertical-align:top;width:2%;">
                        <sup>
                         4
                        </sup>
                       </td>
                       <td style="text-align:justify;">
                        The following table lists the acceptable set of electives that may be taken to satisfy the upper-division electives for the CS major. The electives have been grouped into seven suggested tracks. The tracks group related electives that a student may wish to take in order to achieve a level of expertise in the indicated area. However, it is not mandatory to take any track and students are free to mix and match courses from different tracks to fit their specific interests.
                        <a href="#tt3636" id="tt3636" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180802&amp;print', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" rel="remote /ajax/preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180802&amp;display_options[location]=tooltip&amp;show" target="_blank">
                         COSC 494
                        </a>
                        <span style="display: none !important">
                        </span>
                        , and
                        <a href="#tt1415" id="tt1415" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180801&amp;print', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" rel="remote /ajax/preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180801&amp;display_options[location]=tooltip&amp;show" target="_blank">
                         COSC 493
                        </a>
                        <span style="display: none !important">
                        </span>
                        , may be taken to satisfy the upper-division electives. Up to two COSC 5XX or ECE 5XX courses may count as upper-division elections.
                        <a href="#tt6632" id="tt6632" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184328&amp;print', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" rel="remote /ajax/preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184328&amp;display_options[location]=tooltip&amp;show" target="_blank">
                         COSC 422
                        </a>
                        <span style="display: none !important">
                        </span>
                        does not count as an acceptable elective.
                       </td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                       <td style="text-align:center;vertical-align:top;width:2%;">
                        <sup>
                         5
                        </sup>
                       </td>
                       <td style="text-align:justify;">
                        Any courses not already required for the major.
                       </td>
                      </tr>

                    <h2>
                     <a name="ComputerScienceMajor–HonorsConcentration">
                     </a>
                     <a id="core_47277" name="computersciencemajor–honorsconcentration">
                     </a>
                     Computer Science Major – Honors Concentration
                    </h2>
                    <hr/>
                    <p>
                     In addition to satisfying the requirements for the electrical engineering, computer engineering, or computer science major, candidates for the honors concentration must also complete the following requirements.
                    </p>
                    <ul>
                     <li>
                      Maintain an overall GPA of 3.4.
                     </li>
                     <li>
                      Four 100- or 200-level honors courses* (14 hours minimum, at least two courses must be from Materials Science and Engineering, Engineering Fundamentals, Physics, Math, Chemistry, Biology, Statistics, or
                      <a href="#tt5411" id="tt5411" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=183945&amp;print', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" rel="remote /ajax/preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=183945&amp;display_options[location]=tooltip&amp;show" target="_blank">
                       MSE 117 - Honors: Materials Chemistry
                      </a>
                      <span style="display: none !important">
                      </span>
                      or
                      <a href="#tt6696" id="tt6696" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=183306&amp;print', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" rel="remote /ajax/preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=183306&amp;display_options[location]=tooltip&amp;show" target="_blank">
                       MSE 207
                      </a>
                      <span style="display: none !important">
                      </span>
                      ).
                     </li>
                     <li>
                      Two upper-division honors courses in computer science or electrical and computer engineering (
                      <a href="#tt2827" id="tt2827" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=182985&amp;print', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" rel="remote /ajax/preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=182985&amp;display_options[location]=tooltip&amp;show" target="_blank">

                     <tbody>

                       </td>

                        While most students fulfill this requirement with 100- and 200-level courses, students may substitute upper level courses on approval of the Honors faculty.

                   <div class="acalog-core">
                    <h2>
                     <a name="ComputerScienceMajor–FiveYearBSMSProgram">
                     </a>
                     <a id="core_45699" name="computersciencemajor–fiveyearbsmsprogram">
                     </a>
                     Computer Science Major – Five-Year BS/MS Program
                    </h2>
                    <hr/>
                    <p>
                     The department offers a Five-Year BS-MS program for qualified students. The primary component of the program is that qualified students may take up to 9 hours of approved graduate courses for their senior undergraduate electives and have them count toward both their bachelor’s and master’s degrees at the University of Tennessee. This program is designed for students attending the University of Tennessee for their Master of Science degree because other universities may not accept these courses for graduate credit since they were used to satisfy requirements for the Bachelor of Science degree. Significant components of the program are:
                    </p>
                    <ul>
                     <li>
                      Students must have an overall GPA of at least 3.4 to be admitted to the program. Conditional admission may be granted after completing 64 hours of required coursework while full admission is granted after completing 96 hours of required coursework with a minimum overall GPA of 3.4.
                     </li>
                     <li>
                      Students must at least have conditional admission before taking graduate courses for both their bachelor’s and master’s degrees. All courses taken for graduate credit must be approved by the departmental chair of the program. Students admitted to the program must request permission from the Graduate School to take approved courses for graduate credit.
                     </li>
                     <li>
                      Students admitted to the program must also follow the normal procedure for admission to the Graduate School. Admission of students into this program must be approved by the department and the Graduate School.
                     </li>
                     <li>
                      Students will not be eligible for graduate assistantships until they are enrolled as graduate-level students in the Graduate School.
                     </li>
                    </ul>
                   </div>
                  </div>
                 </td>
                </tr>
               </tbody>
              </table>

                   <div>
                    <h3>
                     COSC 101 - Introduction to Programming
                    </h3>
                    <strong>
                     3
                    </strong>
                    <strong>
                     Credit Hours
                    </strong>
                    <hr/>
                    An introduction to computational thinking and structured programming. Topics include problem solving and algorithm development with emphasis on conditional if/else statements, loop based iteration, and function calls. Students will also be given an overview of commonly used data structures such as arrays. Skills learned include designing a program to solving a problem, developing the algorithms needed, writing code to implement them, testing the code and correcting errors, as well as documenting how the code works.
                    <br/>
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                    </em>

                    <h3>
                     MATH 131 - Calculus 1A Infused with Precalculus
                    </h3>
                    <strong>
                     3
                    </strong>
                    <strong>
                     Credit Hours
                    </strong>
                    <hr/>
                    Single variable calculus, infused with precalculus, especially for students of science, engineering, mathematics, and computer science. Differential calculus with applications and relevant precalculus.
                    <br/>
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                    </em>
                    <em>
                     Credit Restriction:
                    </em>
                    Students who receive a grade of C or better in
                    <a aria-label="MATH 141 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=181625" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=181625'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ?                     <a aria-label="MATH 147 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=181627" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=181627'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     MATH 147
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *, or
                    <a aria-label="MATH 152 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=181630" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=181630'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ?                     <h3>
                     ENGL 101 - English Composition I
                    </h3>
                    <strong>
                     3
                    </strong>
                    <strong>
                     Credit Hours
                    </strong>
                    <hr/>
                    Intensive instruction in writing, focusing on analysis and argument. Strategies for reading critically, analyzing texts from diverse perspectives, developing substantive arguments through systematic revision, addressing specific audiences, integrating sources, and expressing ideas with clarity and correctness.
                    <br/>
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     <strong>
                      Satisfies Volunteer Core Requirement:
                     </strong>
                    </em>
                    (WC)
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     <strong>
                      Satisfies General Education Requirement through the 2021-2022 academic catalog:
                     </strong>
                    </em>
                    (WC)
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                    </em>
                    <em>
                     Grading Restriction:
                    </em>
                    ABC/N grading only.
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     Credit Restriction:
                    </em>
                    Students with credit for
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 118 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180925" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180925'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     ENGL 118
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *,
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 131 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180927" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180927'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     ENGL 131
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *, or
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 198 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=183351" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=183351'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     ENGL 198
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    * may not receive credit for ENGL 101*.
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     Comment(s):
                    </em>
                    Students wishing additional help with writing should also register for
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 103 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180923" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180923'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ?                      ENGL 103
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    .

                   <div>
                    <h3>
                     ENGL 118 - Honors: English Composition
                    </h3>
                    <strong>
                     3
                    </strong>
                    <strong>
                     Credit Hours
                    </strong>
                    <hr/>
                    Grading scale and workload are same as in regular sequence though course proceeds at an accelerated pace. Emphasis on argumentation, critical inquiry, rhetorical analysis, and research methods. May include the study of a long work of literature or nonfiction in addition to a selection of interdisciplinary readings.
                    <br/>
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     <strong>
                      Satisfies Volunteer Core Requirement:
                     </strong>
                    </em>
                    (WC)
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     <strong>
                      Satisfies General Education Requirement through the 2021-2022 academic catalog:
                     </strong>
                    </em>
                    (WC)
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                    </em>
                    <em>
                     Grading Restriction:
                    </em>
                    ABC/N grading only.
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     Credit Restriction:
                    </em>
                    Students with credit for
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 101 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180921" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180921'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     ENGL 101
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *,
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 131 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180927" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180927'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     ENGL 131
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *, or
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 198 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=183351" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=183351'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     ENGL 198
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    * may not receive credit for ENGL 118*.
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     Comment(s):
                    </em>
                    ACT English and composite scores at or above 29 or SAT critical reading and composite scores of 680 and 1280 required. Students receiving a passing grade below B in ENGL 118* will complete the English Composition requirement by taking
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 102 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180922" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180922'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     ENGL 102
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *. Students receiving a grade of B or better will complete their freshman English requirements by choosing
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 102 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180922" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180922'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     ENGL 102
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *, a sophomore-level course in the English Department, or
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 355 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180964" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180964'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     ENGL 355
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *.
                    <br/>

                   <div>
                    <h3>
                     ENGL 131 - Composition for Non-Native Speakers of English I
                    </h3>
                    <strong>
                     3
                    </strong>
                    <strong>
                     Credit Hours
                    </strong>
                    <hr/>
                    Intensive instruction in writing, focusing on analysis and argument. Strategies for developing substantive arguments through systematic revision, addressing specific audiences, integrating sources, and expressing ideas with clarity and correctness. Individual conferences.
                    <br/>
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     <strong>
                      Satisfies Volunteer Core Requirement:
                     </strong>
                    </em>
                    (WC)
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     <strong>
                      Satisfies General Education Requirement through the 2021-2022 academic catalog:
                     </strong>
                    </em>
                    (WC)
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                    </em>
                    <em>
                     Grading Restriction:
                    </em>
                    ABC/N grading only.
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     Credit Restriction:
                    </em>
                    Students with credit for
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 101 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180921" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180921'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     ENGL 101
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *,
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 118 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180925" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180925'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     ENGL 118
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *, or
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 198 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=183351" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=183351'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     ENGL 198
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    * may not receive credit for ENGL 131*.
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     Comment(s):
                    </em>
                    Admission based on TOEFL, IELTS, ACT, or SAT score, or by English Placement Exam.
                    <br/>
                   </div>
                  </td>
                 </tr>
                </tbody>
               </table>

                   <div>
                    <h3>
                     ENGL 198 - Chancellor’s Honors Writing I
                    </h3>
                    <strong>
                     3
                    </strong>
                    <strong>
                     Credit Hours
                    </strong>
                    <hr/>
                    Intensive writing and research instruction, with emphasis on critical inquiry, rhetorical analysis, persuasion/argumentation, and primary and secondary source research. Course topic includes exploration of debates concerning “human nature.” Includes the study of longer works of nonfiction in addition to a selection of interdisciplinary readings.
                    <br/>
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     <strong>
                      Satisfies Volunteer Core Requirement:
                     </strong>
                    </em>
                    (WC)
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     <strong>
                      Satisfies General Education Requirement through the 2021-2022 academic catalog:
                     </strong>
                    </em>
                    (WC)
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                    </em>
                    <em>
                     Grading Restriction:
                    </em>
                    ABC/N grading only.
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     Credit Restriction:
                    </em>
                    Students who receive a grade of C or better in ENGL 198* may not subsequently receive credit for
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 101 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180921" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180921'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     ENGL 101
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *,
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 131 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180927" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180927'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     ENGL 131
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *, or
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 118 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180925" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180925'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     ENGL 118
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *.
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     Comment(s):
                    </em>
                    Restricted to Chancellor’s Honors Program students.
                    <br/>

                   <div>
                    <h3>
                     EF 142 - Introduction to Physics and Modeling for Engineers II
                    </h3>
                    <strong>
                     4
                    </strong>
                    <strong>
                     Credit Hours
                    </strong>
                    <hr/>
                    An introduction to physics concepts for engineering, ways to model these concepts using numerical methods, and skills and practices necessary for a successful engineering career. Topics include work-energy principle, conservation of energy and momentum, application of physics in circular motion, numerical methods applications for modeling highlighted physics concepts, exploration of engineering disciplines, teamwork, project management, and communication skills. Skills learned will include the ability to apply physics concepts to real-world problems, ability to use programming software to model physics concepts, and the ability to recognize and practice concepts related to successful engineering practice such as working in teams, project management, and effective communication.
                    <br/>
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     <strong>
                      Satisfies Volunteer Core Requirement:
                     </strong>
                    </em>
                    (EI)
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                    </em>
                    <em>
                     Grading Restriction:
                    </em>
                    Letter grade only.
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     (RE) Prerequisite(s):
                    </em>
                    <a aria-label="EF 141 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184335" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184335'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     EF 141
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    * and
                    <a aria-label="MATH 131 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184018" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184018'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     MATH 131
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    .
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     (RE) Corequisite(s):
                    </em>
                    <a aria-label="MATH 132 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184019" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184019'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     MATH 132
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *.
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     Registration Restriction(s):
                    </em>
                    Majors in the College of Engineering or Biosystems Engineering.
                    <br/>
                   </div>
                  </td>
                 </tr>

                    <h3>
                     EF 151 - Physics for Engineers I
                    </h3>
                    <strong>
                     4
                    </strong>
                    <strong>
                     Credit Hours
                    </strong>
                    <hr/>
                    Calculus-based study of basic physics concepts, including vectors, kinematics, Newton’s laws, forces, work-energy, and impulse-momentum. Introduction to team work. Introduction to the engineering disciplines. Examination of engineering principles and design issues. Oral and written presentation skills.
                    <br/>
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     <strong>
                      Satisfies Volunteer Core Requirement:
                     </strong>
                    </em>
                    (EI) (NS)

                    </em>
                    (NS)

                   <div>
                    <h3>
                     COSC 102 - Introduction to Computer Science
                    </h3>
                    <strong>
                     4
                    </strong>
                    <strong>
                     Credit Hours
                    </strong>
                    <hr/>
                    Modular programming in an object-oriented programming language, including string and vector manipulation, file I/O, bit operators, Boolean algebra, pointers, simple sorting and binary search, plus introductions to recursion and templates.
                    <br/>
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     Contact Hour Distribution:
                    </em>
                    <em>
                     3 hours lecture and 1 lab.
                    </em>
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     Grading Restriction:
                    </em>
                    Letter grade only.
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     Credit Restriction:
                    </em>
                    Students who have received credit for
                    <a aria-label="COSC 202 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184326" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184326'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     COSC 202
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    or
                    <a aria-label="COSC 230 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184327" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184327'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     COSC 230
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    may not receive subsequent credit for COSC 102.
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     (RE) Prerequisite(s):
                    </em>
                    <a aria-label="COSC 101 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184123" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184123'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     COSC 101
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    with a grade of C or better.
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     (RE) Corequisite(s):
                    </em>
                    <a aria-label="MATH 132 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184019" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184019'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     MATH 132
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>

                    </h3>
                    <strong>
                     4

                    </strong>

                    </em>

                    </em>

                    <h3>
                     MATH 131 - Calculus 1A Infused with Precalculus
                    </h3>
                    <strong>
                     3
                    </strong>
                    <strong>
                     Credit Hours
                    </strong>
                    <hr/>
                    Single variable calculus, infused with precalculus, especially for students of science, engineering, mathematics, and computer science. Differential calculus with applications and relevant precalculus.
                    <br/>
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                    </em>
                    <em>
                     Credit Restriction:
                    </em>

                     MATH 147
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">

                    <a aria-label="MATH 152 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=181630" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=181630'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ?                     <h3>
                     ENGL 102 - English Composition II
                    </h3>
                    <strong>
                     3
                    </strong>
                    <strong>
                     Credit Hours
                    </strong>
                    <hr/>
                    Advancing concepts introduced in
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 101 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180921" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180921'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     ENGL 101
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *. Intensive writing instruction focused on inquiry and research. Strategies for formulating and investigating questions, locating and evaluating information, using varied sources and research methods, developing positions on intercultural and interdisciplinary issues from diverse texts (print, digital, and multimedia), and presenting research using appropriate rhetorical conventions.
                    <br/>
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     <strong>
                      Satisfies Volunteer Core Requirement:
                     </strong>
                    </em>
                    (WC)
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     <strong>
                      Satisfies General Education Requirement through the 2021-2022 academic catalog:
                     </strong>
                    </em>
                    (WC)
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                    </em>
                    <em>
                     Grading Restriction:
                    </em>
                    ABC/N grading only.
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     Credit Restriction:
                    </em>
                    Students with credit for
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 132 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180928" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180928'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     ENGL 132
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *,
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 298 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=183398" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=183398'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     ENGL 298
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *, or
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 290 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=183354" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=183354'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     ENGL 290
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    * may not receive credit for ENGL 102*.
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     (RE) Prerequisite(s):
                    </em>
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 101 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180921" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180921'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     ENGL 101
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *.
                    <br/>

                    </em>
                    Students wishing additional help with writing should also register for
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 104 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180924" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180924'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ?                      ENGL 104
                    </a>

                    </span>

                     ENGL 132 - Composition for Non-Native Speakers of English II

                    Advancing concepts introduced in
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 131 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180927" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180927'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ?                      ENGL 101
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *. Intensive writing instruction focused on inquiry and research. Strategies for formulating and investigating questions, locating and evaluating information, using varied sources and research methods, developing positions on intercultural and interdisciplinary issues from diverse texts (print, digital, and multimedia), and presenting research using appropriate rhetorical conventions.                    <div>
                    <h3>
                     ENGL 290 - Intermediate Writing and Research
                    </h3>
                    <strong>
                     3
                    </strong>
                    <strong>
                     Credit Hours
                    </strong>
                    <hr/>
                    Intensive practice in conducting and writing original research. Critiquing current scholarship to determine gaps in a research problem; locating, organizing, evaluating, integrating, and documenting diverse sources in order to construct and support research-based arguments; identifying salient features of different kinds of researched writing.
                    <br/>
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     <strong>
                      Satisfies Volunteer Core Requirement:
                     </strong>
                    </em>
                    (WC)
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     <strong>
                      Satisfies General Education Requirement through the 2021-2022 academic catalog:
                     </strong>
                    </em>
                    (WC)
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                    </em>
                    <em>
                     Grading Restriction:
                    </em>
                    ABC/N grading only.
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     Credit Restriction:
                    </em>
                    Students with credit for
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 102 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180922" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180922'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     ENGL 102
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *,
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 132 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180928" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180928'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     ENGL 132
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *, or
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 298 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=183398" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=183398'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     ENGL 298
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    * may not receive credit for ENGL 290*.
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     (RE) Prerequisite(s):
                    </em>
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 101 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180921" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180921'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     ENGL 101
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    * through AP Credit.
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     Comment(s):
                    </em>
                    Students are required to have ACT English and composite scores at or above 29 or SAT critical reading and composite scores of 680 and 1280. This course completes the first-year composition requirement.
                    <br/>
                   </div>
                  </td>
                 </tr>
                </tbody>
               </table>

                    <h3>
                     ENGL 298 - Chancellor’s Honors Writing II
                    </h3>
                    <strong>
                     3
                    </strong>
                    <strong>
                     Credit Hours
                    </strong>
                    <hr/>
                    Intensive writing and research instruction to build upon
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 198 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=183351" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=183351'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     ENGL 198
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *, with emphasis on strategies for conducting independent research, locating and evaluating information, using varied sources and research methods, developing positions based on evidence, and writing up research using appropriate conventions within different disciplines. Course topic includes exploration of debates concerning the pursuit of truth and knowledge within different disciplines.
                    <br/>
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     <strong>
                      Satisfies Volunteer Core Requirement:
                     </strong>
                    </em>
                    (WC)
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     <strong>
                      Satisfies General Education Requirement through the 2021-2022 academic catalog:
                     </strong>
                    </em>
                    (WC)
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                    </em>
                    <em>
                     Grading Restriction:
                    </em>
                    ABC/N grading only.
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     Credit Restriction:
                    </em>
                    Students who receive a grade of C or better in ENGL 298* may not subsequently receive credit for
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 102 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180922" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180922'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ?                      ENGL 102
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *,
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 132 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180928" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180928'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     ENGL 132
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *, or
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 290 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=183354" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=183354'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ?                      ENGL 290
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *.
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     (RE) Prerequisite(s):
                    </em>
                    <a aria-label="ENGL 198 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=183351" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=183351'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ?                      ENGL 198

                    </em>

                    <a aria-label="MATH 142 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=181626" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=181626'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ?                      MATH 147
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *.
                    <br/>

                     Comment(s):
                    </em>
                    Students should have a 32 mathematics ACT score or a 700 quantitative SAT score and credit for
                    <a aria-label="MATH 132 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184019" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184019'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ?                     <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    * or
                    <a aria-label="MATH 141 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=181625" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=181625'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     MATH 141
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *, an AP Calculus score of 5, or permission of the instructor to enroll.
                    <br/>
                   </div>
                  </td>
                 </tr>
                </tbody>

                   <div>
                    <h3>
                     EF 152 - Physics for Engineers II
                    </h3>
                    <strong>
                     4
                    </strong>
                    <strong>
                     Credit Hours
                    </strong>
                    <hr/>
                    Calculus-based study of basic physics concepts, including rotational dynamics, statics, oscillations, waves, fluids, heat and temperature, and first and second law of thermodynamics. Introduction to team work. Introduction to the engineering disciplines, examination of engineering principles and design issues. Oral and written presentation skills.
                    <br/>
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     <strong>
                      Satisfies Volunteer Core Requirement:
                     </strong>
                    </em>
                    (EI) (NS)
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     <strong>
                      Satisfies General Education Requirement through the 2021-2022 academic catalog:
                     </strong>
                    </em>
                    (NS)
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                    </em>
                    <em>
                     (RE) Prerequisite(s):
                    </em>
                    <a aria-label="EF 151 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180901" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180901'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     EF 151
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    * with a grade of C or better, or
                    <a aria-label="EF 142 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184336" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184336'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     EF 142
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    * with a grade of C or better.
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     (RE) Corequisite(s):
                    </em>
                    <a aria-label="MATH 142 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=181626" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=181626'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     MATH 142
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *.
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     Registration Restriction(s):
                    </em>
                    Tickle College of Engineering or biosystems engineering majors.
                    <br/>
                   </div>
                  </td>
                 </tr>
                </tbody>
               </table>

                   <div>
                    <h3>
                     BIOL 101 - Introduction to Biology: Cells, Genetics, and Physiology
                    </h3>
                    <strong>
                     4
                    </strong>
                    <strong>
                     Credit Hours
                    </strong>
                    <hr/>
                    For non-biology majors, introduction to the principles of biology as they relate to cellular and organismal level processes. Topics include cell structure and major fundamental metabolic processes such as energy flow in biological systems, protein synthesis, and aspects of genetics. Includes a survey of human anatomy and physiology with topics relating to human health.
                    <br/>
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     <strong>
                      Satisfies Volunteer Core Requirement:
                     </strong>
                    </em>
                    (NS)
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     <strong>
                      Satisfies General Education Requirement through the 2021-2022 academic catalog:
                     </strong>
                    </em>
                    (NS)
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     Contact Hour Distribution:
                    </em>
                    <em>
                     3 hours lecture and one 2-hour lab.
                    </em>
                    <br/>
                   </div>
                  </td>
                 </tr>
                </tbody>
               </table>

                   <div>
                    <h3>
                     BIOL 150 - Organismal and Ecological Biology
                    </h3>
                    <strong>
                     3
                    </strong>
                    <strong>
                     Credit Hours
                    </strong>
                    <hr/>
                    Intended for science majors, an introduction to the major biological concepts emphasizing the organismal and ecological aspects of life. Organized along themes of evolution, structure and function, information flow, exchange and storage, pathways of energy and matter, and systems.
                    <br/>
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     <strong>
                      Satisfies Volunteer Core Requirement:
                     </strong>
                    </em>
                    (NS)
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     <strong>
                      Satisfies General Education Requirement through the 2021-2022 academic catalog:
                     </strong>
                    </em>
                    (NS)
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     Contact Hour Distribution:
                    </em>
                    <em>
                     2 hours lecture and one 1-hour biological literacy session (BioLit).
                    </em>
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     Credit Restriction:
                    </em>
                    Students may not receive credit for both BIOL 150* and
                    <a aria-label="BIOL 158 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=183014" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=183014'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     BIOL 158
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    .
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     Comment(s):
                    </em>
                    Although not required, it is recommended that BIOL 150* and
                    <a aria-label="BIOL 160 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=183013" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=183013'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     BIOL 160
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    * be taken in sequence.
                    <br/>
                   </div>
                  </td>
                 </tr>
                </tbody>
               </table>

                   <div>
                    <h3>
                     CHEM 102 - Principles of Chemistry
                    </h3>
                    <strong>
                     3
                    </strong>
                    <strong>
                     Credit Hours
                    </strong>
                    <hr/>
                    A general course in theoretical and descriptive chemistry. Modern atomic theory, chemical bonding, molecular structures and geometries, stoichiometry, quantitative aspects of solution chemistry, thermochemistry, intermolecular forces, gas laws, kinetics, and nuclear chemistry.
                    <br/>
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     <strong>
                      Satisfies Volunteer Core Requirement:
                     </strong>
                    </em>
                    (NS)
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     <strong>
                      Satisfies General Education Requirement through the 2021-2022 academic catalog:
                     </strong>
                    </em>
                    (NS)
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                    </em>
                    <em>
                     Credit Restriction:
                    </em>
                    Credit may be received for only one of the following courses – CHEM 100, CHEM 102*, CHEM 120,
                    <a aria-label="CHEM 122 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184144" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184144'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     CHEM 122
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *, or
                    <a aria-label="CHEM 128 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180669" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180669'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     CHEM 128
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *.
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     (RE) Corequisite(s):
                    </em>
                    <a aria-label="CHEM 103 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184140" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184140'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     CHEM 103
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *.
                    <br/>
                   </div>

                    <h3>
                     CHEM 122 - General Chemistry I
                    </h3>
                    <strong>
                     3
                    </strong>
                    <strong>
                     Credit Hours
                    </strong>
                    <hr/>
                    A general course in theoretical and descriptive chemistry. Modern atomic theory, chemical bonding, molecular structures and geometries, stoichiometry, and quantitative aspects of solution chemistry, gas laws, and chemical energy.
                    <br/>
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     <strong>
                      Satisfies Volunteer Core Requirement:
                     </strong>
                    </em>
                    (NS)
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     <strong>
                      Satisfies General Education Requirement through the 2021-2022 academic catalog:
                     </strong>
                    </em>
                    (NS)
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                    </em>
                    <em>
                     Credit Restriction:
                    </em>
                    Credit may be received for only one of the following courses – CHEM 100,
                    <a aria-label="CHEM 102 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184139" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184139'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     CHEM 102
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *, CHEM 120, CHEM 122*, or
                    <a aria-label="CHEM 128 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180669" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180669'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     CHEM 128
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *.
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     (RE) Prerequisite(s):
                    </em>
                    <a aria-label="MATH 119 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=181621" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=181621'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     MATH 119
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    or Math ACT score of 25 or higher or SAT Math score of 620 or higher.
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     (RE) Corequisite(s):
                    </em>
                    <a aria-label="CHEM 123 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184145" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184145'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ?                    <div>
                    <h3>
                     CHEM 128 - Honors: General Chemistry I
                    </h3>
                    <strong>
                     4
                    </strong>
                    <strong>
                     Credit Hours
                    </strong>
                    <hr/>
                    A sophisticated treatment of the principles of chemistry designed for students who are well prepared for a thorough and systematic study of chemistry. Topics include atomic structure and bonding, molecular structure, spectroscopy, chemical reactions and stoichiometry, introduction to organic compounds and reactions, intermolecular forces and phase transitions, behavior of gases.
                    <br/>
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     <strong>
                      Satisfies Volunteer Core Requirement:
                     </strong>
                    </em>
                    (NS)
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     <strong>
                      Satisfies General Education Requirement through the 2021-2022 academic catalog:
                     </strong>
                    </em>
                    (NS)
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     Contact Hour Distribution:
                    </em>
                    <em>
                     3 hours and 1 lab.
                    </em>
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     Credit Restriction:
                    </em>
                    Credit may be received for only one of the following courses or sequences –
                    <a aria-label="CHEM 112 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184141" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184141'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     CHEM 112
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *-
                    <a aria-label="CHEM 113 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184142" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184142'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     CHEM 113
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *,
                    <a aria-label="CHEM 122 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184144" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184144'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     CHEM 122
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    *-

                     CHEM 123

                     (DE) Prerequisite(s):
                    </em>
                    ACT Composite score of 30 or higher or permission of instructor.

                    <h3>
                     PHYS 231 - Fundamentals of Physics: Electricity and Magnetism
                    </h3>
                    <strong>
                     3
                    </strong>

                    For engineers and majors in mathematics and the physical sciences. Electric and magnetic phenomena including DC and AC circuits and electromagnetic waves.

                     </strong>

                     </strong>

                   <div>
                    <h3>
                     EF 141 - Introduction to Physics and Modeling for Engineers I
                    </h3>
                    <strong>
                     4
                    </strong>
                    <strong>
                     Credit Hours
                    </strong>
                    <hr/>
                    An introduction to physics concepts for engineering, ways to model these concepts using numerical methods, and skills and practices necessary for a successful engineering career. Topics include vectors, kinematics, Newton’s Laws, forces, numerical methods applications for modeling highlighted physics concepts, and an introduction to the university, exploration of engineering disciplines, and personal, academic, and professional skills development. Skills learned will include the ability to apply physics concepts to real-world problems, ability to use programming software to model physics concepts, and the ability to recognize and practice concepts related to successful engineering practice such as time management and a working knowledge of tools and strategies valuable to engineering study.
                    <br/>
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     <strong>
                      Satisfies Volunteer Core Requirement:
                     </strong>
                    </em>
                    (EI)
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                    </em>
                    <em>
                     Grading Restriction:
                    </em>
                    Letter grade only.
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     (RE) Corequisite(s):
                    </em>
                    <a aria-label="MATH 131 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184018" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=184018'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     MATH 131
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    .
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     Comment(s):
                    </em>
                    Students who receive any grade in
                    <a aria-label="EF 151 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180901" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180901'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     EF 151
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    * or
                    <a aria-label="EF 157 opens a new window" href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180903" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=34&amp;coid=180903'+((location.search.match(/&amp;print/i)) ? '&amp;print' : '')+'', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" target="_blank">
                     EF 157
                    </a>
                    <span style="display: none !important">
                    </span>
                    * may not register for EF 141 without instructor permission.
                    <br/>
                    <em>
                     Registration Restriction(s):
                    </em>
                    Majors in the College of Engineering or Biosystems Engineering.
                    <br/>
                   </div>
                  </td>
                 </tr>
